Share this...FacebookTwitterObviously the German Weather Service (DWD) just couldn‚Äôt be bothered to update the chart it prominently features as part of its website logo. Perhaps it‚Äôs because an updated version¬†would completely spoil the desired message of ‚Äúuninterrupted warming‚Äú.

Figure 1: Part of the DWD internet logo totally misleads the public. Source of graphic: DWD
The chart-part of the DWD logo is definitely misleading, and likely controversial legally. Notice how the curve starts to fade already in 2005 (compare to Figure 2 below) and ends in the warm year of 2007, conveniently leaving out the colder years that follow, which would almost totally spoil the impression of warming.
Worse, only the section from about 1975 [correction: 1955] to 2006 is shown ‚Äì the only section that shows real warming from the entire 120-year long chart. The rest is ignored!
No wonder Harald Martensen was fooled and bought a house at the Baltic Sea, thinking it would become the new Mediterranean.
Apparently the DWD allowed former Chancellor Gerhard Schr√∂der to have a peek at the up-to-date chart. Schr√∂der went ahead and purchased a home¬†down south in sunny, warm Turkey, which is supposed to burn up because of global warming.


